Title : Lamina (neuropil)
Text : The '''lamina''' is the most peripheral [[neuropil]] of the [[insect visual system]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vigier|first=P|title=Mecanisme de la synthese des impressions lumineuses recueilles par les yeux composes des Dipteres|journal=C. R. Acad. Sci. Paris|date=1909|volume=148|pages=1221–1223}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Cajal|first=S.R.|author2=Sanchez, D.|title=Contribución al conocimiento de los centros nerviosos de los insectos. Parte I Retina y centros opticos.|journal=Trab. Lab. Invest. Biol. Univ. Madrid|date=1915|volume=13|pages=1–168|doi=10.5962/bhl.title.37839}}</ref> There are twelve distinct neuron classes in the lamina: the [[lamina monopolar cell]]s L1-L5, two [[GABA]]ergic feedback neurons (C2 and C3), two wide-field feedback neurons (Lawf1 and Lawf2), lamina intrinsic amacrine neurons (Lai)  and the T1 basket cell.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fischbach|first=KF|author2=Dittrich, AP;|title=The optic lobe of Drosophila melanogaster. I. A Golgi analysis of wild-type structure. Cell Tissue Res.|journal=Cell and Tissue Research|date=1989|volume=258|issue=3|pages=441–475|doi=10.1007/bf00218858}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Tuthill|first=JC|author2=Nern, A; Holtz, SL; Rubin, GM; Reiser, MB|title=Contributions of the 12 neuron classes in the fly lamina to motion vision.|journal=Neuron|date=July 10, 2013|volume=79|issue=1|pages=128–40|pmid=23849200|doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2013.05.024|pmc=3806040}}</ref> The outer [[Simple eye in invertebrates|photoreceptor]]s, R1-R6, terminate in the lamina, where they form tetrad synapses with L1, L2, L3, and Lai.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meinertzhagen|first=IA|author2=O'Neil, SD|title=Synaptic organization of columnar elements in the lamina of the wild type in Drosophila melanogaster.|journal=The Journal of Comparative Neurology|date=March 8, 1991|volume=305|issue=2|pages=232–63|pmid=1902848|doi=10.1002/cne.903050206}}</ref>

